{"title_page": "Basoda State", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox former subdivision\n|native_name = \u092c\u0938\u094b\u0926\u093e \u0930\u093f\u092f\u093e\u0938\u0924\n|conventional_long_name =Hydergarh Basoda State \n|common_name =Basoda\n|nation = [[British India]]\n|status_text = [[Princely State]]\n|era = \n|year_start = 1753\n|date_start = \n|event_start= \n|year_end = 1947\n|date_end = \n|event_end= [[Independence of India|Accession to the Indian Union]]\n|event1 = \n|date_event1 = \n|p1 =\n|s1 = India\n|flag_p1 = \n|flag_s1 = Flag of India.svg\n|image_flag =\n|image_coat = \n|image_map = Basoda-Muhammadgarh map.jpg\n|image_map_caption = Basoda State in the [[Imperial Gazetteer of India]]\n|stat_area1 = 104\n|stat_year1 =[[1901 Census of India]]\n|stat_pop1 =4,897 \n|footnotes =\n|demonym=|capital=|today=}}\n'''Basoda State''' was a former [[princely state]] in Central India, part of the [[Bhopal Agency]] during the [[British Raj]]. It was situated in the [[Malwa Plateau]]. Basoda was a small state, its headquarters were at [[Ganj Basoda]]. The state had an area of 104 km<sup>2</sup>, and a population of 4,897 in 1901.<ref name=\"TGI\">[http://members.iinet.net.au/~royalty/ips/b/basoda.html Basoda (Princely State)]</ref>\n\nThis state was also known as '''Nawab-Basoda''' or '''Haidargarh-Basoda''' in order to distinguish it from a place with the same name in [[Gwalior State]].<ref name=\"IGI\">[http://dsal.uchicago.edu/reference/gazetteer/pager.html?objectid=DS405.1.I34_V07_111.gif Imperial Gazetteer of India, v. 7, p. 105.]</ref> \n==History==\n\nBasoda state was established in 1753 by Muhammad Ahsanullah Khan son of Muhammad Diler Khan founder of [[Kurwai State]].<ref name=\"IGI\"/><ref name=\"TGI\"/> The rulers of the state were of [[Pathans of Madhya Pradesh|Pashtun]] origin, related to the ruling families of [[Mohammadgarh State|Mohammadgarh]] and [[Kurwai State|Kurwai]] states. Between 1817 and 1822 Basoda was occupied by [[Gwalior State]]. In 1822 Basoda became a [[British protectorate]] until 1947, when its last ruler, Nawab Masood Ali Khan, signed the accession to the [[Dominion of India|Indian Union]].<ref>{{cite book| title=Imperial Gazetteer of India, Central India, vol. 12|pages= 282\u2013283|year=1908| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xQC2AAAAIAAJ }}</ref> \n\n===Rulers===\nRulers of Basoda held the title of ''[[Nawab]]''.<ref>[http://www.worldstatesmen.org/India_princes_A-J.html Princely States of India]</ref> \n\n====Nawabs====\n\n*1753 \u2013 1786           Nawab     Ahsanullah Khan                    (d. 1786) \n*1786 \u2013 1800             Nawab   Baqaullah Khan \n*1800 \u2013 1817             Nawab   Asad `Ali Khan (1st time) \n*1817 \u2013 1822               \u2013 [[Interregnum]] \u2013 Basoda occupied by Gwalior\n*1822 \u2013 1864              Nawab  Asad `Ali Khan (2nd time) \n* 6 February 1864 \u2013 1896        Nawab `Omar `Ali Khan                     (b. c.1830 \u2013 d. ....) \n*12 Jun 1896 \u2013  2 July 1929 Nawab Haideralikhanr `Ali Khan Firuz Jung         (b. 1854 \u2013 d. 19..) \n*1929 \u2013 15 August 1947     Nawab    Mohammad Ayyub `Ali Khan Firuz Jung (d. 1947)\n*   (not ruling)                     Nawab Masood Ali Khan\n*                        Nawab Kishwar Ali Khan, present Nawab\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Pashtun empires and dynasties]]\n*[[List of Sunni Muslim dynasties]]\n*[[Political integration of India]]\n*[[Pathans of Madhya Pradesh]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord|23.85|N|77.93|E|region:IN_type:landmark_source:kolossus-svwiki|display=title}}\n{{MP Princely States}}\n[[Category:Vidisha district]]\n[[Category:Muslim princely states of India]]\n[[Category:Pashtun dynasties]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox former subdivision\n|native_name = \u092c\u0938\u094b\u0926\u093e \u0930\u093f\u092f\u093e\u0938\u0924\n|conventional_long_name =Hydergarh Basoda State \n|common_name =Basoda\n|nation = [[British India]]\n|status_text = [[Princely State]]\n|era = \n|year_start = 1753\n|date_start = \n|event_start= \n|year_end = 1947\n|date_end = \n|event_end= [[Independence of India|Accession to the Indian Union]]\n|event1 = \n|date_event1 = \n|p1 =\n|s1 = India\n|flag_p1 = \n|flag_s1 = Flag of India.svg\n|image_flag =\n|image_coat = \n|image_map = Basoda-Muhammadgarh map.jpg\n|image_map_caption = Basoda State in the [[Imperial Gazetteer of India]]\n|stat_area1 = 104\n|stat_year1 =[[1901 Census of India]]\n|stat_pop1 =4,897 \n|footnotes =\n|demonym=|capital=|today=}}\n'''Basoda State''' was a former [[princely state]] in Central India, part of the [[Bhopal Agency]] during the [[British Raj]]. It was situated in the [[Malwa Plateau]]. Basoda was a small state, its headquarters were at [[Ganj Basoda]]. The state had an area of 104 km<sup>2</sup>, and a population of 4,897 in 1901.<ref name=\"TGI\">[http://members.iinet.net.au/~royalty/ips/b/basoda.html Basoda (Princely State)]</ref>\n\nThis state was also known as '''Nawab-Basoda''' or '''Haidargarh-Basoda''' in order to distinguish it from a place with the same name in [[Gwalior State]].<ref name=\"IGI\">[http://dsal.uchicago.edu/reference/gazetteer/pager.html?objectid=DS405.1.I34_V07_111.gif Imperial Gazetteer of India, v. 7, p. 105.]</ref> \n==History==\n\nBasoda state was established in 1753 by Muhammad Ahsanullah Khan son of Muhammad Diler Khan founder of [[Kurwai State]].<ref name=\"IGI\"/><ref name=\"TGI\"/> The rulers of the state were of [[Pathans of Madhya Pradesh|Pashtun]] origin, related to the ruling families of [[Mohammadgarh State|Mohammadgarh]] and [[Kurwai State|Kurwai]] states. Between 1817 and 1822 Basoda was occupied by [[Gwalior State]]. In 1822 Basoda became a [[British protectorate]] until 1947, when its last ruler, Nawab Masood Ali Khan, signed the accession to the [[Indian Union]].<ref>{{cite book| title=Imperial Gazetteer of India, Central India, vol. 12|pages= 282\u2013283|year=1908| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xQC2AAAAIAAJ }}</ref> \n\n===Rulers===\nRulers of Basoda held the title of ''[[Nawab]]''.<ref>[http://www.worldstatesmen.org/India_princes_A-J.html Princely States of India]</ref> \n\n====Nawabs====\n\n*1753 - 1786           Nawab     Ahsanullah Khan                    (d. 1786) \n*1786 - 1800             Nawab   Baqaullah Khan \n*1800 - 1817             Nawab   Asad `Ali Khan (1st time) \n*1817 - 1822               - [[Interregnum]] - Basoda occupied by Gwalior\n*1822 - 1864              Nawab  Asad `Ali Khan (2nd time) \n* 6 Feb 1864 - 1896        Nawab `Omar `Ali Khan                     (b. c.1830 - d. ....) \n*12 Jun 1896 -  2 Jul 1929 Nawab Haideralikhanr `Ali Khan Firuz Jung         (b. 1854 - d. 19..) \n*1929 - 15 Aug 1947     Nawab    Mohammad Ayyub `Ali Khan Firuz Jung (d. 1947)\n*   (not ruling)                     Nawab Masood Ali Khan\n*                        Nawab Kishwar Ali Khan, present Nawab\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Pashtun empires and dynasties]]\n*[[List of Sunni Muslim dynasties]]\n*[[Political integration of India]]\n*[[Pathans of Madhya Pradesh]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord|23.85|N|77.93|E|region:IN_type:landmark_source:kolossus-svwiki|display=title}}\n{{MP Princely States}}\n[[Category:Vidisha district]]\n[[Category:Muslim princely states of India]]\n[[Category:Pashtun dynasties]]\n", "name_user": "DrKay", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixeddashesusing ascript, date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Basoda_State"}
{"title_page": "The Best American Mystery Stories 1997", "text_new": "'''''The Best American Mystery Stories 1997''''',<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://aux.avclub.com/the-best-american-mystery-stories-1997-1798194175|title=: The Best American Mystery Stories 1997|last=Krewson|first=John|work=AUX|access-date=2018-09-12|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book...b.../the-best-american-mystery-stories-1997|title=Kirkus Reviews|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> a volume in ''[[The Best American Mystery Stories]] series'', was edited by guest editor [[Robert B. Parker]] with [[Otto Penzler]].<ref>Parker, Robert B. and Otto Penzler(editors), ''The Best American Mystery Stories 1997'', Boston: Houghton Mifflin Harcourt, 2013.</ref> The series editor chooses about fifty article candidates, from which the guest editor picks 20 or so for publication; the remaining runner-up articles listed in the appendix.\n\n==Mystery Stories included==\n{|\n|-\n|'''Author''' || '''Story''' || '''Source'''\n|-\n|[[Doug Allyn]] || \"Blind Lemon\" ||  ''[[Alfred Hitchcock's Mystery Magazine]]''\n|-\n|[[James Crumley]] || \"Hot Springs\" || ''[[Murder for Love]]''\n|-\n|[[Jeffery Deaver]] || \"The Weekender\" || ''[[Alfred Hitchcock's Mystery Magazine]]''\n|-\n|[[Brendan DuBois]] || \"The Dark Snow\" || ''[[Playboy]]''\n|-\n|[[Elizabeth George]] || \"The Surprise of His Life\" || ''[[Women on the Case]]''\n|-\n|[[Jeremiah Healy]] || \"Eyes That Never Meet\" || ''[[Unusual Suspects (anthology)|Unusual Suspects]]''\n|-\n|[[Melodie Johnson Howe]] || \"Another Tented Evening\" || ''[[Ellery Queen's Mystery Magazine]]''\n|-\n|[[Pat Jordan]] || \"The Mark\" || ''[[Playboy]]''\n|-\n|[[Jonathan Kellerman]] || \"The Things We Do for Love\" ||'' [[Murder for Love]]''\n|-\n|[[Andrew Klavan]] || \"Lou Monahan, County Prosecutor\" || ''Guilty as Charged''\n|-\n|[[Elmore Leonard]] || \"Karen Makes Out\" || ''[[Murder for Love]]''\n|-\n