{"title_page": "2018 Illinois gubernatorial election", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2016}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name = 2018 Illinois gubernatorial election\n| country = Illinois\n| type = presidential\n| ongoing = no\n| previous_election = 2014 Illinois gubernatorial election\n| previous_year = 2014\n| next_election = 2022 Illinois gubernatorial election\n| next_year = 2022\n| election_date = {{Start date|2018|11|6}}\n| turnout = 56.15% {{increase}} 7.99 [[percentage point|pp]]\n| image1 = [[File:JB Pritzker at Gold Star Mothers Luncheon (cropped) (1).jpg|x150px]]\n| nominee1 = '''[[J. B. Pritzker]]'''\n| party1 = Democratic Party (United States)\n| running_mate1 = '''[[Juliana Stratton]]'''\n| popular_vote1 = '''2,479,746'''\n| percentage1 = '''54.5%'''\n| image2 = [[File:Bruce Rauner crop.jpg|x150px]]\n| nominee2 = [[Bruce Rauner]]\n| running_mate2 = [[Evelyn Sanguinetti]]\n| party2 = Republican Party (United States)\n| popular_vote2 = 1,765,751\n| percentage2 = 38.8%\n| map_image = Illinois Governor Election Results by County, 2018.svg\n| map_size = 150px\n| map_caption = County results<br>'''Pritzker:''' {{legend0|#a5b0ff|40\u201350%}} {{legend0|#7996e2|50\u201360%}} {{legend0|#584cde|70\u201380%}}<br/>'''Rauner:''' {{legend0|#ffc8cd|30\u201340%}} {{legend0|#ffb2b2|40\u201350%}} {{legend0|#e27f7f|50\u201360%}} {{legend0|#d75d5d|60\u201370%}} {{legend0|#d72f30|70\u201380%}}\n| title = [[Governor of Illinois|Governor]]\n| before_election = [[Bruce Rauner]]\n| before_party = Republican Party (United States)\n| after_election = [[J. B. Pritzker]]\n| after_party = Democratic Party (United States)\n}}\n{{ElectionsIL}}\n\nThe '''2018 Illinois gubernatorial election''' took place on November 6, 2018, to elect the [[Governor of Illinois]], concurrently with the [[2018 Illinois elections|2018 Illinois general election]]. Incumbent [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] Governor [[Bruce Rauner]] ran for re-election to a second term in office,<ref name=\":9\">{{cite news |last=Contreras |first=Daisy |last2=Driscoll |first2=Jaclyn |url=http://www.nprillinois.org/post/republicans-tout-unity-after-divisive-primary-challenging-general-election-ahead#stream/0 |title=Republicans Tout Unity After Divisive Primary, Challenging General Election Ahead |work=NPR Illinois |date=August 16, 2018 |accessdate=2018-08-18 }}</ref> but was defeated by [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nominee [[J. B. Pritzker]]. This was the second consecutive Illinois gubernatorial election in which the incumbent unsuccessfully sought re-election.\n\n==Election information==\nThe primaries and general elections coincided with those for federal [[2018 United States House of Representatives elections in Illinois|congressional races]] and those for other state offices. The election was part of the [[2018 Illinois elections]].\n\n===Turnout===\nFor the primary election, turnout was 25.76%, with 2,046,710 votes cast.<ref name=turnoutprimary>{{cite web |title=Voter Turnout |url=https://www.elections.il.gov/ElectionOperations/VoterTurnout.aspx?MID=fVf30XCcBCY%3d&T=637204877664537563 |website=www.elections.il.gov |publisher=Illinois State Board of Elections |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"result\">{{cite web |title=Election Results |url=https://www.elections.il.gov/ElectionOperations/ElectionVoteTotals.aspx |website=www.elections.il.gov |publisher=Illinois State Board of Elections |accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref> For the general election, turnout was 56.15%, with 4,547,657 votes cast.<ref name=turnoutgen>{{cite web |title=Voter Turnout |url=https://www.elections.il.gov/ElectionOperations/VoterTurnout.aspx?MID=fVf30XCcBCY%3d&T=637204879738085590 |website=www.elections.il.gov |publisher=Illinois State Board of Elections |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"result\"/>\n\n==Democratic primary==\n[[File:Gubernatorial candidates blank Illinois primary ballot 20180310 232153.jpg|thumb|upright=1.25|Democratic candidates listed on a blank ballot]]\n<!-- CITATIONS MUST BE PROVIDED. THIS IS WIKIPEDIA, NOT A TRIAL BALLOON. ALL UNCITED ENTRIES WILL BE DELETED. LIST CANDIDATES IN ALPHABETICAL ORDER-->\n===Candidates===\n====Nominated====\n* [[J. B. Pritzker]], venture capitalist<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/politics/ct-jb-pritzker-governor-announcement-met-20170406-story.html|title=J.B. Pritzker joins Illinois governor race, facing big Democratic field to take on Rauner|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|last=Pearson|first=Rick|date=April 6, 2017|accessdate=6 April 2017}}</ref>\n:* Running mate: [[Juliana Stratton]], [[Illinois House of Representatives|State Representative]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Miller|first=Rich|title=Pritzker to pick Rep. Stratton|date=August 9, 2017|newspaper=[[Capitol Fax]]|location=[[Springfield, Illinois]]|accessdate=August 10, 2017|url=https://capitolfax.com/2017/08/09/pritzker-to-pick-rep-stratton/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810063726/https://capitolfax.com/2017/08/09/pritzker-to-pick-rep-stratton/|archive-date=August 10, 2017|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n====Eliminated in primary====\n* [[Daniel Biss]], [[Illinois Senate|State Senator]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pearson|first1=Rick|title=State Sen. Daniel Biss announces Democratic bid for governor|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/politics/ct-daniel-biss-illinois-governor-race-met-0320-20170319-story.html|accessdate=20 March 2017|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=20 March 2017}}</ref>\n:* Running mate: [[Litesa Wallace]], state representative<ref>{{cite news|url=https://capitolfax.com/2017/09/08/biss-formally-announces-litesa-wallace-as-new-running-mate/|title=Biss formally announces Litesa Wallace as new running mate|date=September 8, 2017|accessdate=September 8, 2017|last=Miller|first=Rich|newspaper=[[Capitol Fax]]}}</ref>\n:*Former running mate: [[Carlos Ramirez-Rosa]], [[Chicago City Council|Chicago Alderman]]\n* Bob Daiber, [[Madison County, Illinois|Madison County]] Regional Superintendent of Schools<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bnd.com/news/local/article131961239.html|title=Madison County school superintendent to run for governor|last=Koziatek|first=Mike|newspaper=[[Belleville News-Democrat]]|location=[[Belleville, Illinois]]|date=February 10, 2017|accessdate=February 10, 2017}}</ref>\n:* Running mate: Jonathan W. Todd, social worker<ref>{{cite news|last=Miller|first=Rich|title=Daiber names social worker as running mate|date=October 13, 2017|newspaper=[[Capitol Fax]]|location=[[Springfield, Illinois]]|accessdate=October 13, 2017|url=https://capitolfax.com/2017/10/13/daiber-names-social-worker-as-running-mate/}}</ref>\n* Tio Hardiman, former director of [[Cure Violence|CeaseFire]] and candidate for governor in 2014<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pjstar.com/news/20170605/nick-in-am-tio-hardiman-to-run-again-for-illinois-governor|title=Nick in the AM: Tio Hardiman to run again for Illinois governor|work=[[Journal Star (Peoria)|Peoria Journal Star]]|last=Vlahos|first=Nick|date=June 5, 2017|accessdate=June 5, 2017}}</ref>\n:* Running mate: Patricia Avery, President and CEO of the [[Champaign County, Illinois|Champaign County]] chapter of the [[NAACP]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Miller|first=Rich|title=Hardiman selects running mate|date=August 9, 2017|newspaper=[[Capitol Fax]]|location=[[Springfield, Illinois]]|accessdate=August 10, 2017|url=https://capitolfax.com/2017/08/09/hardiman-selects-running-mate/}}</ref>\n* [[Christopher G. Kennedy|Chris Kennedy]], former chairman of the [[University of Illinois system|University of Illinois Board of Trustees]] and member of the [[Kennedy family]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://chicago.suntimes.com/news/chris-kennedy-announces-run-for-governor/|title=Chris Kennedy Announces Run For Governor|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|last=Sneed|first=Michael|date=February 8, 2017|accessdate=February 8, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170209045715/ht