}}\n\n===Results===\n[[File:Illinois gubernatorial Republican primary, 2018.svg|thumb|upright|Results by county\n{{collapsible list\n|title=Map legend\n|{{legend|#cc0000|Rauner\u201460\u201370%}}\n|{{legend|#ef2929|Rauner\u201450\u201360%}}\n|{{legend|#888a85|Tie}}\n|{{legend|#fce94f|Ives\u201450\u201360%}}\n|{{legend|#edd400|Ives\u201460\u201370%}}\n<ref name=\"nytimes.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/03/20/us/elections/results-illinois-primary-elections.html|title=Illinois Primary Election Results|first=The New York|last=Times|date=March 20, 2018|accessdate=May 22, 2018|website=Nytimes.com}}</ref>\n}}\n]]\n\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title = Republican primary results<ref name=\"result\"/>\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = [[Bruce Rauner]] (incumbent)\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = 372,124\n| percentage = 51.53\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = [[Jeanne Ives]]\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = 350,038\n| percentage = 48.47\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = 744,248\n| percentage = 100.00\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\nDespite a 14% decrease in Republican primary votes cast, Rauner increased his overall vote total by 9% compared to the 2014 primary. In 2018, he managed to capture a narrow majority of the votes, with 51.4%, in his victory over conservative Ives. Rauner only received 40.2% of the primary vote in 2014, in his narrow win victory over Kirk Dillard, Bill Brady, and Dan Rutherford.\n\nRauner did well in central Illinois compared to the Republican primary four years earlier, when he managed 30% in the downstate region and finished 2nd to Kirk Dillard. In 2018, he carried the region with 52%.\n\nHowever, the result was still considered surprisingly close, and indicated widespread dissatisfaction with Rauner's governorship among more conservative Republicans.<ref>https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2018/3/20/17144724/illinois-gov-bruce-rauner-republican-primary</ref>\n\n==Third parties and independents==\nIn order to qualify as an established party in Illinois, a candidate for said party must earn at least 5% of the vote in a statewide election. This last occurred in 2006, when [[Rich Whitney]] won 10% of the vote, allowing the [[Illinois Green Party]] to achieve such status. Established party status comes with benefits. For example, candidates of an established party needs only 5,000 voter signatures on its petitions to gain ballot access. For non-established parties this number is approximately 25,000.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kaergard|first=Chris|title=Presidential race may boost Illinois Libertarian party's state chances|date=October 2, 2016|newspaper=[[Journal Star (Peoria)|Peoria Journal Star]]|accessdate=October 6, 2017|url=http://www.pjstar.com/news/20161002/presidential-race-may-boost-illinois-libertarian-partys-state-chances}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Wheelhouse|first=Bill|title=The Fall Of the Illinois Green Party|date=September 8, 2014|newspaper=[[WILL|Illinois Public Media]]|accessdate=October 6, 2017|url=https://will.illinois.edu/news/story/the-fall-of-the-illinois-green-party}}</ref>\n\nFor the 2018 election, non-established parties do not need to run a full slate in order to qualify for ballot access.<ref>{{cite news|last=Driscoll|first=Jaclyn|title=Court Ruling Ends Illinois Full-Slate Election Requirements For 'Third Parties'|date=October 2, 2017|newspaper=[[WILL|Illinois Public Media]]|accessdate=October 6, 2017|url=http://nprillinois.org/post/court-ruling-ends-illinois-full-slate-election-requirements-third-parties#stream/0}}</ref>\n\n===Conservative===\n[[Sam McCann]], a longtime intraparty opponent of Bruce Rauner, resigned from the Republican Caucus to run for governor as a member of the newly created Conservative Party.<ref name=\"McCann Announcement\">{{cite news|last=Miller|first=Rich|title=Sen. Sam McCann announces for governor as Conservative Party candidate|date=April 19, 2018|newspaper=[[Capitol Fax]]|accessdate=April 19, 2018|url=https://capitolfax.com/2018/04/19/sen-sam-mccann-announces-for-governor-as-conservative-party-candidate/}}</ref>\n\n====Candidates====\n* [[Sam McCann]], state senator<ref name=\"McCann Announcement\"/>\n** Running mate: Aaron Merreighn, activist and [[United States Marine Corps]] veteran<ref name=\"McCann Announcement\"/>\n\n===Libertarian===\n[[Kash Jackson]] was the Libertarian nominee. Libertarian nominees for governor, other statewide offices, and the [[Illinois General Assembly|General Assembly]] were chosen by the [[Libertarian Party of Illinois]] at a state [[political convention|convention]] on March 3, 2018 in [[Bloomington, Illinois]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://lpillinois.org/convention/schedule.php | title = 2018 Convention Schedule of Events | publisher = Libertarian Party of Illinois | location = Bloomington, Illinois | accessdate = 2018-02-22 }}</ref> Jackson appeared on the ballot.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sj-r.com/news/20180625/libertarians-file-nearly-double-signatures-required-to-get-on-illinois-ballot|title=Libertarians file nearly double signatures required to get on Illinois ballot|last=Schoenburg|first=Bernard|work=The State Journal|access-date=2018-07-24|language=en}}</ref>\n\n====Candidates====\n\n* Kash Jackson, navy veteran and activist<ref name=\"LP-Tribune\">{{cite web |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/chicagoinc/ct-wrestler-running-for-governor-0622-chicago-inc-20170621-story.html|title=Former pro-wrestler with ties to Kellyanne Conway seeks Illinois governor nod|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|last=Janssen|first=Kim|date=June 21, 2017|accessdate=June 23, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://denver.cbslocal.com/2016/09/04/navy-vet-on-cross-country-mission-for-parental-equality/|title=Navy Vet On Cross-Country Mission For Parental Equality|date=September 4, 2016|website=Denver.cbslocal.com|accessdate=May 22, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"pg-nom\">{{Cite web|title = Libertarian party selects governor candidate in Bloomington|url = http://www.pantagraph.com/news/state-and-regional/illinois/government-and-politics/elections/libertarian-party-selects-governor-candidate-in-bloomington/article_01ac31d5-0600-57f9-a2bd-f27db2501c51.html|website = The Pantagraph|date=March 3, 2018|accessdate = March 4, 2018}}</ref>\n**Running mate: Sanj Mohip<ref name=\"pantagraph.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pantagraph.com/news/state-and-regional/illinois/government-and-politics/elections/libertarian-party-selects-governor-candidate-in-bloomington/article_01ac31d5-0600-57f9-a2bd-f27db2501c51.html|title=Libertarian party selects governor candidate in Bloomington|author=Julia Evelsizer|website=Pantagraph.com|accessdate=May 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Endorsements====\n{{Endorsements box\n| title = Kash Jackson\n| list =\n;Notable Individuals\n* [[Austin Petersen]], [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian]] candidate for President of the United States in [[2016 United States presidential election|2016]] and candidate for U.S Senate in Missouri for [[United States Senate election in Missouri, 2018|2018]]<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/KashJackson2018/status/980964840092110848|title=Had dinner with two Freedom Fighters @merissahamilton and @AP4Liberty . Strength can be found in working with others to further the goal of maximizing freedom. #RestoringFreedom#GoldRush2018|author=Kash Jackson|work=Twitter}}</ref>\n* [[Larry Sharpe (politician)|Larry Sharpe]], business consultant and candidate for Vice President of the United States in 2016, Libertarian nominee for [[New York Governor]] [[New York gubernatorial election, 2018|2018]]<ref name=\"Twitter\">{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/TeaPartyerRhian/status/970820155382161408|title=Twitter|website=Twitter.com|accessdate=22 May 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n\n====Unsuccessful====\n* Matthew C. Scaro, entrepreneur and Libertarian activist<ref name=\"LP-Tribune\" />\n* Jon Stewart, retired professional wrestler, Republican candidate for the state house in 1998 and Republican candidate for [[Illinois's 5th congressional district|IL-05]] in [[Illinois's 5th congressional district special election, 2009|2009]]<ref name=\"LP-Tribune\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://aquarianagrarian.blogspot.com/2017/03/libertarian-party-of-chicago-vets.html|title=The Aquarian Agrarian: Libertarian Party of Chicago Vets Illinois Governor Candidates|date=March 8, 2017|website=Aquarianagrarian.blogspot.com|accessdate=May 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Independents ===\n====Removed from ballot====\n* Mary Vann-Metcalf<ref name=\"torial.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.torial.com/en/jake.leonard/portfolio/335980|title=Libertarian Party files nearly 48,000 signatures for ballot access - Jake Leonard - torial|website=Torial.com|accessdate=March 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.wttw.com/2018/06/25/illinois-governor-s-race-widens|title=Illinois Governor\u2019s Race Widens|website=WTTW News|accessdate=March 8, 2019}}</ref>\n* Gregg Moore<ref name=\"torial.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.elections.il.gov/ElectionInformation/ObjectionDetail.aspx?ObjectionID=yyBHBMiKtNmPrtWHGRI1Xw==&ElectionID=HoA6yhqrFAE=|title=Objection Details|website=Elections.il.gov|accessdate=March 8, 2019}}</ref>\n**Magistrale Morgan\n* Dock Walls, perennial candidate<ref name=\"Walls Campaign\">{{cite news|url=https://capitolfax.com/2018/04/23/a-dock-walls-jim-tobin-gubernatorial-ticket/|title=A Dock Walls, Jim Tobin gubernatorial ticket?|last=Miller|first=Rich|date=April 23, 2018|newspaper=[[Capitol Fax]]|accessdate=April 25, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.elections.il.gov/ElectionInformation/ObjectionDetail.aspx?ObjectionID=6ry8EBiXF1LlG2buyBvDcg==&ElectionID=HoA6yhqrFAE=|title=Objection Details|website=Elections.il.gov|accessdate=March 8, 2019}}</ref>\n**[[Jim Tobin (activist)|Jim Tobin]], founder of Taxpayers United of America<ref name=\"Walls Campaign\" />\n\n====Withdrew====\n* William J. Kelly, radio host and [[perennial candidate]] (subsequently ran on Constitution Party ticket, then withdrew)<ref name=\"wjk-taps-tranchant\" /><ref name=\"ivesjoins\" />\n** Running mate: Brian Leggero, candidate for Mayor of [[Rockford, Illinois|Rockford]] in 2017<ref name=\"kellyleggero\" />\n\n=== Constitution ===\n====Nominee====\nWilliam J. Kelly was nominated for governor and Chad Koppie, a member of the Kane County Regional Board of School Trustees, were chosen to run as the gubernatorial ticket of the Illinois Constitution Party. However, on June 5, 2018, Kelly dropped out and endorsed the third party campaign of Sam McCann.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://springfielddaily.com/politics/2018-election/illinois-constitution-party-selects-william-j-kelly-for-governor/|title=Illinois Constitution Party Selects William J. Kelly for Governor|last=Monack|first=Joseph|date=March 16, 2018|newspaper=Springfield Daily|accessdate=April 27, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"thirdpartyballot\">{{cite news|url=http://www.sj-r.com/news/20180325/third-parties-seeking-attention-ballot-access-in-illinois |title=Third parties seeking attention, ballot access in Illinois (Part 1 of 3)|last=Kwiatkowski|first=Maximilian|date=March 25, 2018|newspaper=State Journal Registrar|accessdate=April 22, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://springfielddaily.com/politics/2018-election/illinois-constitution-party-selects-william-j-kelly-for-governor/|title=Illinois Constitution Party Selects William J. Kelly for Governor|website=Springfielddaily.com|accessdate=May 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=====Withdrew=====\n* William J. Kelly, radio host and [[perennial candidate]] (endorsed Sam McCann)<ref name=\"Kelly Drops Out\">{{cite news|url=https://springfielddaily.com/politics/illinois-govt/kelly-leaves-race-endorses-mccann-for-governor/|title=Kelly leaves race, endorses McCann for Governor|author=Staff Contributor|date=June 5, 2018|newspaper=Springfield Daily|accessdate=June 11, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Randy Stufflebeam]], chairman of the Illinois Constitution Party (endorsed William J. Kelly)\n\n===Green Party===\nThe Green Party ran a slate of statewide candidates in 2006 and 2010, but failed to be placed on the ballot in 2014<ref name=\"autogenerated7\">{{cite web|url=http://wuis.org/post/green-party-candidates-seek-place-november-ballot|title=Green Party Candidates Seek Place on November Ballot|last1=Vinicky|first1=Amanda|last2=Meisel|first2=Hannah|date=27 March 2014|website=Wuis.org|accessdate=14 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Greens\">[http://www.miamiherald.com/2014/08/22/4303510/illinois-november-ballot-set-without.html Rauner Dealt Double Blows Over Illinois Ballot] ''Miami Herald'', August 22, 2014. Retrieved August 25, 2014</ref> and declined to run any statewide candidates in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://springfielddaily.com/politics/2018-election/no-statewide-candidates-after-illinois-green-party-convention/|title=No Statewide Candidates After Illinois Green Party Convention|first=Joseph|last=Monack|date=March 28, 2018|website=Springfielddaily.com|accessdate=March 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{notelist|group=noballotaccess}}\n\n==General election==\n[[Bruce Rauner]] had been rated as one of the, if not the most, vulnerable governors running for re-election in 2018 by [[Politico]] and the [[National Journal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/02/23/top-10-governors-races-2018-423308|title=The top 10 governor's races of 2018|website=Politico.com|accessdate=May 22, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nationaljournal.com/s/665672/why-bruce-rauner-is-most-vulnerable-governor|title=Why Bruce Rauner Is the Most Vulnerable Governor|website=Nationaljournal.com|accessdate=May 22, 2018}}</ref> Following his surprisingly narrow primary win, Rauner offered former state senator [[Karen McConnaughay]], attorney general nominee [[Erika Harold]], [[Chicago Cubs]] co-owner and [[Republican National Committee]] Finance Chair [[Todd Ricketts]] and [[Illinois Republican Party]] Committeeman Richard Porter the chance to replace him on the ticket, with the promise that he would continue to fully fund the campaign using his personal wealth.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/politics/ct-met-pritzker-trump-governors-meeting-20181213-story.html|title=Sensing re-election loss, Gov. Bruce Rauner looked to replace himself on Nov. 6 ballot|first=Rick|last=Pearson|website=Chicagotribune.com|accessdate=March 8, 2019}}</ref> Rauner consistently trailed in the polls by large margins, and the race was rated as a likely Democratic win by the majority of election prognosticators. Ultimately, Rauner remained on the ballot, and lost in the most lopsided gubernatorial election since [[Jim Edgar]] was reelected in [[Illinois gubernatorial election, 1994|1994]].\n\n===Endorsements===\n{{Endorsements box\n| title = Bruce Rauner (R)\n| list =\n;U.S. Governors\n* [[Eric Greitens]] (R-[[Missouri]]; resigned office June 1, 2018)<ref name=WIMOIN>{{cite web|last=Pearson|first=Rick|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/politics/ct-met-bruce-rauner-madigan-ad-20171024-story.html|title=Rauner recruits neighboring governors to rip Madigan on tax hike|website=[[Chicago Tribune]]|accessdate=October 30, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Eric Holcomb]] (R-[[Indiana]])<ref name=WIMOIN/>\n* [[Scott Walker (politician)|Scott Walker]] (R-[[Wisconsin]])<ref name=WIMOIN/>\n;Illinois State Senators\n* Senator [[John Curran (Illinois politician)|John Curran]] (R-[[Woodridge, Illinois|Woodridge]])<ref name=\"dprn\">{{cite news|title=DuPage County Elected Leaders Endorse Governor Rauner|date=January 22, 2018|work=Citizens for Rauner|accessdate=February 4, 2018|url=https://www.brucerauner.com/news/dupage-county-elected-leaders-endorse-governor-rauner/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180205001053/https://www.brucerauner.com/news/dupage-county-elected-leaders-endorse-governor-rauner/|archivedat