7\n| align=center| \u00b1 4.4%\n| align=center| 19%\n| {{party shading/Democratic}} align=center| '''38%'''\n| {{party shading/Undecided}} align=center| '''43%'''\n|}\n\n;with Bruce Rauner and Dick Durbin\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- valign=bottom\n! Poll source\n! Date(s)<br>administered\n! Sample<br>size\n! Margin<br>of error\n! style=\"width:100px;\"| Bruce<br>Rauner (R)\n! style=\"width:100px;\"| Dick<br>Durbin (D)\n! Undecided\n|-\n| [http://www.illinoisobserver.net/2016/08/02/poll-durbin-leads-rauner-9-points/ We Ask America]\n| align=center| July 26, 2016\n| align=center| 824\n| align=center| \u00b1 3.5%\n| align=center| 35%\n| {{party shading/Democratic}} align=center| '''44%'''\n| align=center| 22%\n|}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n===Results===\nPritzker only won 16 out of [[Illinois]]\u2019 102 counties. However, those counties account for more than half of the state's total population. In the end, the election was not close with the Pritzker/Stratton ticket defeating the Rauner/Sanguinetti ticket by almost 16 percentage points. Pritzker won the traditionally Democratic [[Cook County]] which includes the [[Chicago Metropolitan Area]]. Pritzker also won in all but one of [[Chicago]]\u2019s collar counties, which used to be more of a tossup in years prior. Pritzker also did well in other cities such as [[East Saint Louis]] and [[Champaign]], and narrowly winning in [[Peoria, Illinois|Peoria]]. Rauner did well in most rural areas of the state, but it was not enough to put a dent into Pritzker\u2019s lead. Pritzker and Stratton were sworn in on January 14, 2019.  \n{{Election box begin| title=Illinois gubernatorial election, 2018<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.elections.il.gov/ElectionResults.aspx?ID=jwAfLjnmELI=|title=Election Results|website=Elections.il.gov|accessdate=March 8, 2019}}</ref>}}\n\n[[File:Illinois Governor Election Results by County, 2018 (McCann).svg|thumb|upright|Support for McCann by county\n{{collapsible list\n|title=Map legend\n|{{legend|#003a13|>35%}}\n|{{legend|#005522|30\u201335%}}\n|{{legend|#00aa44|20\u201325%}}\n|{{legend|#00d455|15\u201320%}}\n|{{legend|#00ec66|10\u201315%}}\n|{{legend|#2aff80|5\u201310%}}\n|{{legend|#7bff9c|<5%}}\n}}\n]]\n\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link \n| candidate  =  [[J. B. Pritzker]]\n| party      = Democratic Party (United States)\n  |votes      = 2,479,746\n  |percentage = 54.53%\n|change = +8.18%\n  }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link \n| candidate  = [[Bruce Rauner]] (incumbent)\n| party      = Republican Party (United States)\n  |votes      = 1,765,751\n  |percentage = 38.83%\n|change = -11.44%\n  }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link \n| candidate  = [[Sam McCann]]\n| party      = Conservative Party (United States)\n  | votes      = 192,527\n  | percentage = 4.23%\n| change = N/A\n  }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link \n| candidate  = [[Kash Jackson]]\n| party      = Libertarian Party (United States)\n  | votes      = 109,518\n  | percentage = 2.40%\n| change = -0.95%\n  }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link \n| candidate  = Write-ins\n| party      = n/a\n  | votes      = 115\n  | percentage = 0.01%\n| change = -0.02%\n  }}\n{{Election box total \n  | votes      ='''4,547,657'''\n  | percentage = '''100.0%'''\n|change = N/A\n}}\n{{Election box gain with party link no swing\n| winner     = Democratic Party (United States)\n| loser      = Republican Party (United States)\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[2018 Illinois elections]]\n*[[2018 Illinois Attorney General election]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://votesmart.org/election/2018/G/IL/2018-gubernatorial Candidates] at [[Vote Smart]] \n*[https://ballotpedia.org/Illinois_gubernatorial_election,_2018 Candidates] at [[Ballotpedia]]\n\n;Official campaign websites\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20181018135337/https://www.kash2018.com/ Kash Jackson (L) for Governor]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20181108185137/https://mccannforil