rv|url={{google books |plainurl=y |id=vZ-SB57WBo8C}}}}\n* {{cite book|last=Winn|first=John C.|year=2009|title=That Magic Feeling: The Beatles' Recorded Legacy, Volume Two, 1966\u20131970|publisher=Three Rivers Press|location=New York, NY|isbn=978-0-307-45239-9|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last= Womack |first= Kenneth |authorlink=Kenneth Womack|year= 2007 | title = Long and Winding Roads: The Evolving Artistry of the Beatles|publisher= Continuum |isbn= 978-0-8264-1746-6 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Womack|first=Kenneth|year=2014|title=The Beatles Encyclopedia: Everything Fab Four|publisher=ABC-CLIO|location=Santa Barbara, CA|isbn= 978-0-313-39171-2|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Womack|first=Kenneth|year=2018|title=Sound Pictures: The Life of Beatles Producer George Martin \u2013 The Later Years, 1966\u20132016|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qghODwAAQBAJ|publisher=Chicago Review Press|location=Chicago, IL|isbn=978-0-912777-74-0|ref=harv}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book|editor-last=Ashby|editor-first=Arved Mark|title=The Pleasure of Modernist Music: Listening, Meaning, Intention, Ideology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Pit6yL_Few4C|year=2004|publisher=Boydell & Brewer|isbn=978-1-58046-143-6}}\n* {{cite book|editor-last=Edmondson|editor-first=Jacqueline|title=Music in American Life: An Encyclopedia of the Songs, Styles, Stars, and Stories that Shaped our Culture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TQPXAQAAQBAJ|year=2013|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-0-313-39348-8}}\n* {{cite book|last=Roberts|first=Michael James|title=Tell Tchaikovsky the News: Rock \u2019n\u2019 Roll, the Labor Question, and the Musicians\u2019 Union, 1942\u20131968|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pIBXAwAAQBAJ|year=2014|publisher=Duke University Press|isbn=978-0-8223-7883-9}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links |display=''Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band'' |commonscat=yes |c=Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band\n |d=Q169226 |q=Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band|n=no\n |b=no |m=no|mw= no |s=no  |species=no |species_author=no |v=no|voy= no|wikt=no}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.thebeatles.com/album/sgt-peppers-lonely-hearts-club-band}}\n* {{Discogs master|type=album|23934}}\n\n{{The Beatles albums}}\n{{Sgt. Peppers Lonely Hearts Club Band}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Awards for ''Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band''\n| titlestyle = background: lightblue\n| list1 =\n{{Brit British Album}}\n{{Grammy Award for Album of the Year 1960s}}\n{{Grammy Award for Best Pop Vocal Album}}\n}}\n{{UK best-selling albums (by year) 1956\u20131969}}\n{{UK Christmas No. 1 albums in the 1960s}}\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:1967 albums]]\n[[Category:The Beatles albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by George Martin]]\n[[Category:Albums arranged by Mike Leander]]\n[[Category:Albums arranged by George Martin]]\n[[Category:Albums conducted by George Martin]]\n[[Category:Albums recorded at Abbey Road Studios]]\n[[Category:Capitol Records albums]]\n[[Category:Concept albums]]\n[[Category:Recorded music characters]]\n[[Category:Fictional sergeants]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award for Album of the Year]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award for Best Pop Vocal Album]]\n[[Category:Brit Award for British Album of the Year]]\n[[Category:Parlophone albums]]\n[[Category:Psychedelic music albums by English artists]]\n[[Category:United States National Recording Registry recordings]]\n[[Category:Albums with cover art by Peter Blake (artist)]]\n[[Category:Art rock albums by English artists]]\n[[Category:Baroque pop albums]]\n[[Category:Proto-prog albums]]\n", "name_user": "79.154.175.162", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eRetrospective appraisal)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sgt._Pepper%27s_Lonely_Hearts_Club_Band"}
{"title_page": "Rosie Stephenson-Goodknight", "text_new": "{{short description|American Wikipedia editor, focused on closing its gender gap; Knight of Serbia}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   = Dame\n| name               = Rosie Stephenson-Goodknight\n| other_names        = Rosiestep\n| image              = Rosie Stephenson-Goodknight at WikiConference North America 2019.jpg\n| alt                = \n| caption            = Rosie Stephenson-Goodknight at the WikiConference North America 2018\n| birth_name         = <!-- only use if different from name above -->\n| birth_date         = <!-- {{birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living people supply only the year with {{Birth year and age|YYYY}} unless the exact date is already widely published, as per [[WP:DOB]]. For people who have died, use {{Birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}}. -->\n| birth_place        = \n| death_date         = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place        = \n| death_cause        = \n| burial_place       =  \n| burial_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| nationality        = \n| education          = \n| occupation         = Business administrator\n| years_active       = \n| era                = \n| employer           = \n| organization       = \n| spouse             =  \n| partner            =  \n| children           = 1<ref name=huff/>\n| parents            = \n| relatives          = [[David Albala]] (grandfather)<br />[[Paulina Lebl-Albala]] (grandmother)\n| known for          = [[Wikipedia]] editor\n| awards             = [[Wikipedian of the Year]] (2016)\n| module             = {{Listen| embed=yes |filename = Rosie Stephenson-Goodknight voice en.flac |title = Stephenson-Goodknight's voice |type = speech |description = recorded July 2018}}\n}}\n'''Dame Rosie Gojich Stephenson-Goodknight''',<ref name=\"D+C\" /> known on Wikipedia as '''Rosiestep''', is an American [[Wikipedia]] editor who is noted for her attempts to address [[gender bias on Wikipedia|gender bias in the encyclopedia]] by running a project to increase the quantity and quality of women's [[Biography|biographies]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.houstonchronicle.com/life/article/Adding-women-s-voices-to-Wikipedia-12344424.php|title=Wikipedia editing marathons add women's voices to online resource|work=Houston Chronicle|access-date=November 25, 2017}}</ref><ref name=grauniad/>  She has contributed thousands of new articles and was named co-[[Wikipedian of the Year]] in 2016. In May 2018, she was honored with a Serbian knighthood.\n\n==Early life and education==\n\nStephenson-Goodknight, of [[Serbia]]n descent, is the granddaughter of [[Paulina Lebl-Albala]], an active [[feminist]] who was the president of the University Women of Yugoslavia.<ref name=\"HaanDaskalova2006\">{{cite book|last1=Haan|first1=Francisca de|last2=Daskalova|first2=Krasimira|last3=Loutfi|first3=Anna|title=Biographical Dictionary of Women's Movements and Feminisms in Central, Eastern, and South Eastern Europe: 19th and 20th Centuries|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hsgQjbgBOAkC&pg=PA297|year=2006|publisher=Central European University Press|isbn=978-963-7326-39-4|pages=297\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Vu\u010deti\u0107\">{{cite web|last=Vu\u010deti\u0107|first=Radina|title=The Emancipation of Women in Interwar Belgrade and the \"Cvijeta Zuzori \u0107 \" Society|url=http://www.udi.rs/articles/genderRV.pdf|publisher=Yugoslav Association for Social History}}</ref>  [[David Albala]], her grandfather, was a physician and [[Zionist]] leader, who served for a period as president of [[Belgrade]]'s [[Sephardi]] community.<ref name=\"Radovi\u01072006\">{{Cite web |url=http://web.arhiv.rs/develop/vesti.nsf/feaee540dc011162c1256e7d0032cb98/c0b102b20bee7af8c1257128005d8e8a?OpenDocument |title=Evokacija Srpskog Feminizma S Po\u010detka 20. Veka  |last=Radovi\u0107 |first=Nade\u017eda |date=April 3, 2006 |publisher=Medijska Dokumentacija |language=Serbian |access-date=June 30, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://embassies.gov.il/beograd/NewsAndEvents/Pages/Marking-the-25th-anniversary-of-Israel-Serbia-diplomatic-relations-and-the-.aspx|title=25 Years of the Israel-Serbia Diplomatic Relations|date=December 25, 2017|website=Embassy of Israel|access-date=February 2, 2018}}</ref> At a young age, she displayed a keen interest in world culture, but was discouraged by her father from pursuit of a career in [[anthropology]]; instead she completed a [[Master of Business Administration]] degree.<ref name=huff/>\n\n==Wikipedia editing==\n[[File:Wikimedia Diversity Conference I.jpg|thumb|left|Stephenson-Goodknight at the 2016 Wikimedia Diversity Conference in Washington, D.C.]]\nStephenson-Goodknight began editing Wikipedia in 2007. Her son had edited an article about a town in Ukraine where he was working with the [[Peace Corps]], and told his mother that Wikipedia can be edited by anybody. She began editing later that year when she looked for books published by the [[Book League of America]] and found a gap in the site's knowledge resources.<ref name=\"WM profile\"/> She found the encyclopedia to be a suitable outlet for anthropology, citing [[Margaret Mead]] as an influence:<ref name=huff/><ref name=\"WMblog\">{{cite web|url=https://blog.wikimedia.org/2016/06/24/wikipedians-of-the-year/|title=Jimmy Wales names Emily Temple-Wood and Rosie Stephenson-Goodknight as Wikipedians of the Year|author=Erhart, Ed|publisher=Wikimedia Blog|date=June 24, 2016|accessdate=June 30, 2016 |language=}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|quote=Some of you know that I am a [[cultural anthropologist]] at heart. I wanted to follow in the footsteps of Margaret Mead and study cultural anthropology at Barnard (my mom\u2019s alma mater), like Margaret did. I wanted to travel to [[Papua New Guinea]] and do research on its people, like Margaret did. But my dad said \u2018no\u2019 to majoring in anthropology\u2014he wanted something more practical for my university studies. So now, years later, I get to live the life of an armchair cultural anthropologist, writing articles about Goaribari Island and its cannibals. To all the girls out there with impractical dreams, this article is dedicated to you.|author=|title=|source=}}\n\n[[File:Wikimania 2016 - Opening by Jimmy Wales 19.jpg|thumb|Stephenson-Goodknight at Wikimania 2016 with Wikipedia founder [[Jimmy Wales]]]]\n\nStephenson-Goodknight worked at creating articles on geography, architecture and various biographies for several years, but has more recently concentrated on women's biographies.<ref name=huff/> By 2013, Stephenson-Goodknight was featured in the UK ''[[The Huffington Post|Huffington Post]]'' for having written over 3,000 new articles for Wikipedia, and at that time, over 1000 articles had appeared at the \"Did you know?\" feature on Wikipedia's main page.<ref name=huff/> {{As of|2016}} she has created over 4,000 new articles,<ref group=Note>Total excludes redirects {{cite web|url=https://tools.wmflabs.org/xtools/pages/?user=Rosiestep&lang=en&wiki=wikipedia&namespace=0&redirects=none&limit=1000|title= Pages Created |website=WMFlabs |accessdate=July 8, 2016}}</ref> and has made over 100,000 edits.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"Counter\">{{cite web|title=X!'s tools|url=https://tools.wmflabs.org/xtools-ec/index.php?user=Rosiestep&project=en.wikipedia|website=wmflabs.org|accessdate=July 9, 2016}}</ref> The 2016 [[Wikipedian of the Year]] awards, granted by Wikipedia trustee [[Jimmy Wales]] in recognition of outstanding achievement, named Stephenson-Goodknight as a winner, sharing the award jointly with fellow editor [[Emily Temple-Wood]].<ref name=\":0\" /> At the time of the award, it was noted that over 1,300 of her articles have appeared on Wikipedia's \"Did you know?\".<ref name=\"WMblog\" /> She also co-founded WikiProject Women, WikiProject Women writers, and [[Women in Red]].<ref name=\"WMblog\"/> These projects have increased Wikipedia's percentage of articles on women from 15.5% to 16.35%.<ref name=union>{{cite news|url=http://www.theunion.com/news/localnews/22749884-113/nevada-citys-rosie-stephenson-goodknight-named-co-wikipedian-of-2016 | first=Teresa Yinmeng | last=Liu | title=Nevada City's Rosie Stephenson-Goodknight named co-Wikipedian of 2016 for addressing online gender gap|work=Western Nevada County Union|date=July 3, 2016|accessdate=July 6, 2016}}</ref> She has taken part in related projects such as the ''Art+Feminism Wikipedia Edit-A-Thon'' in April 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.library.unlv.edu/newsblog/2016/02/artfeminism-wikipedia-edit-thon.html|title=Art+Feminism Wikipedia Edit-A-Thon|publisher=University of Nevada, Las Vegas Libraries|date=February 2016|accessdate=June 30, 2016}}</ref>\n\nStephenson-Goodknight believes there is information to write stronger biographies, provided people are prepared to search for it.<ref name=grauniad>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2016/mar/19/women-in-science-on-wikipedia-will-we-ever-fill-the-information-gap|title=Women in science on Wikipedia: will we ever fill the information gap?|first=Molly|last=Redden|work=The Guardian|date=March 19, 2016|accessdate=June 30, 2016}}</ref> She also suggests it is possible for women to contribute greatly to Wikipedia, explaining, \"What Wikipedia needs is you, the female editor, with your unique aptitudes and interests and talkpage tone. Without you, gender imbalance and systemic bias continue on Wikipedia.\"<ref name=huff>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/netha-hussain/rosie-stephenson-the-woma_b_6302636.html|title=Rosie Stephenson: The Woman Who Wrote Over Three Thousand Articles on Wikipedia|last=Hussain | first=Netha|work=Huffington Post|date=February 9, 2015|accessdate=June 30, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nOn January 23, 2020, Stephenson-Goodknight was announced by Wikipedia to be the editor of the [[WP:6M|6,000,000<sup>th</sup> article]] on Wikipedia, namely the article on Canadian author [[Maria Elise Turner Lauder]].<ref name=\"wikipedia_now_more_than_six_million_2020\"> [https://techcrunch.com/2020/01/23/wikipedia-english-six-million-articles/ Wikipedia now has more than 6 million articles in English], Manish Singh, January 23, 2020, techcrunch.com. </ref>\n\n==Awards and distinctions==\n[[File:Rosie Stephenson-Goodknight in Serbia 2.jpg|thumb|upright|Elevation to a Dame of the St. Sava Order of Diplomatic Pacifism, May 2018]]\nOn December 14, 2017, Goodnight was the \"honored guest\" at an event hosted by Israel's ambassador to Serbia, Alona Fisher-Kamm, to commemorate 25 years of diplomatic relations between Serbia and Israel.<ref name=\"D+C\">{{cite web|title=Interview with Rosie Gojich Stephenson-Goodknight: Everyone in Serbia made me feel like 'this is your home'|first=\u017dikica |last=Milo\u0161evi\u0107 |url=http://www.diplomacyandcommerce.rs/interview-with-rosie-gojich-stephenson-goodknight-everyone-in-serbia-made-me-feel-like-this-is-your-home/|website=Diplomacy&Commerce|date=March 2, 2018|accessdate=May 30, 2018|language=en-us}}</ref><ref name=\"EmbassyOfIsrael\">{{cite web|title=25 Years of the Israel-Serbia Diplomatic Relations|url=http://embassies.gov.il/beograd/NewsAndEvents/Pages/Marking-the-25th-anniversary-of-Israel-Serbia-diplomatic-relations-and-the-.aspx|publisher=Embassy of Israel in Serbia|accessdate=30 May 2018|date=25 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn May 29, 2018, in a ceremony conferring honors on those who deserved high diplomatic recognition, Stephenson-Goodnight was appointed a \"[[Knight of the St. Sava Order of Diplomatic Pacifism|Dame of the St. Sava Order of Diplomatic Pacifism]]\" ({{lang|sr|Vitez svetosavskog pacifizma}}) by Deputy Serbian Prime Minister and Minister of Foreign Affairs [[Ivica Da\u010di\u0107]],<ref name=\"Gproxx\">{{citation|author=|title=Serbian Diplomacy Day Marked|date=May 29, 2018|url=https://cordmagazine.com/events/faces-and-places/serbian-diplomacy-day-marked/|work=C or D|location=Belgrade|publisher=Alliance International Media}}<!-- identified as \"prof. Rosie Stephenson-Goodknight, Vice President of Wikimedia District of Columbia\" --></ref> for her work on Wikipedia to preserve the memory of Serbs in the \"hundred years since the Great War\". Mention was specifically made of her contribution towards preserving the memory of the Serbian military officer and Jewish community leader, her grandfather [[David Albala]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.blic.rs/vesti/politika/dacic-dodelio-najvisa-diplomatska-priznanja-medu-laureatima-modna-kreatorka/j3w5jjz|title=Da\u010di\u0107 dodelio najvi\u0161a diplomatska priznanja, me\u0111u laureatima modna kreatorka, humintarac, pre\u017eiveli logora\u0161i Jasenovca\u2026|newspaper=Blic|date=May 29, 2018|accessdate=May 29, 2018 |language=Serbian}}</ref><ref name=\"Gproxx\" />\n\n==Personal life==\nStephenson-Goodknight works in [[Las Vegas]] as a business administrator for a healthcare company, and has homes in that city and in [[Nevada City, California]].<ref name=union /><ref name=\"WM profile\">{{cite web|url=http://blog.wikimedia.org/2013/02/14/a-profile-of-rosie-stephenson-goodknight/|title=Finding inspiration from editing Wikipedia: a profile of Rosie Stephenson-Goodknight|first=Zoe|last=Bernard|publisher=Wikimedia Foundation|date=February 14, 2013|accessdate=June 30, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|United States}}\n* [[List of Wikipedia people]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=Note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Rosie Stephenson-Goodknight}}\n* [https://pro.europeana.eu/post/women-in-culture-and-tech-rosie-stephenson-goodknight Rosie Stephenson Goodknight on Europeana]\n\n{{Wikimedian of the Year|state=autocollapse}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stephenson-Goodknight, Rosie}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:American biographers]]\n[[Category:American encyclopedists]]\n[[Category:American people of Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Sephardic-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Serbian descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Serbian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American science writers]]\n[[Category:American Wikimedians]]\n[[Category:American women non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Knights of the St. Sava Order of Diplomatic Pacifism]]\n[[Category:People from Nevada City, California]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Serbian royalty]]\n[[Category:Wikimedians of the Year]]\n[[Category:Women biographers]]\n[[Category:Women science writers]]\n[[Category:Wikipedia people]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American Wikipedia editor, focused on closing its gender gap; Knight of Serbia}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   = Dame\n| name               = Rosie Stephenson-Goodknight\n| other_names        = Rosiestep\n| image              = Rosie Stephenson-Goodknight at WikiConference North America 2019.jpg\n| alt                = \n| caption            = Rosie Stephenson-Goodknight at the WikiConference North America 2018\n| birth_name         = <!-- only use if different from name above -->\n| birth_date         = <!-- {{birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living people supply only the year with {{Birth year and age|YYYY}} unless the exact date is already widely published, as per [[WP:DOB]]. For people who have died, use {{Birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}}. -->\n| birth_place        = \n| death_date         = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place        = \n| death_cause        = \n| burial_place       =  \n| burial_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| nationality        = \n| education          = \n| occupation         = Business administrator\n| years_active       = \n| era                = \n| employer           = \n| organization       = \n| spouse             =  \n| partner            =  \n| children           = 1<ref name=huff/>\n| parents            = \n| relatives          = [[David Albala]] (grandfather)<br />[[Paulina Lebl-Albala]] (grandmother)\n| known for          = [[Wikipedia]] editor\n| awards             = [[Wikipedian of the Year]] (2016)\n| module             = {{Listen| embed=yes |filename = Rosie Stephenson-Goodknight voice en.flac |title = Stephenson-Goodknight's voice |type = speech |description = recorded July 2018}}\n}}\n'''Dame Rosie Gojich Stephenson-Goodknight''',<ref name=\"D+C\" /> known on Wikipedia as '''Rosiestep''', is an American [[Wikipedia]] editor who is noted for her attempts to address [[gender bias on Wikipedia|gender bias in the encyclopedia]] by running a project to increase the quantity and quality of women's [[Biography|biographies]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.houstonchronicle.com/life/article/Adding-women-s-voices-to-Wikipedia-12344424.php|title=Wikipedia editing marathons add women's voices to online resource|work=Houston Chronicle|access-date=November 25, 2017}}</ref><ref name=grauniad/>  She has contributed thousands of new articles and was named co-[[Wikipedian of the Year]] in 2016. In May 2018, she was honored with a Serbian knighthood.\n\n==Early life and education==\n\nStephenson-Goodknight, of [[Serbia]]n descent, is the granddaughter of [[Paulina Lebl-Albala]], an active [[feminist]] who was the president of the University Women of Yugoslavia.<ref name=\"HaanDaskalova2006\">{{cite book|last1=Haan|first1=Francisca de|last2=Daskalova|first2=Krasimira|last3=Loutfi|first3=Anna|title=Biographical Dictionary of Women's Movements and Feminisms in Central, Eastern, and South Eastern Europe: 19th and 20th Centuries|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hsgQjbgBOAkC&pg=PA297|year=2006|publisher=Central European University Press|isbn=978-963-7326-39-4|pages=297\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Vu\u010deti\u0107\">{{cite web|last=Vu\u010deti\u0107|first=Radina|title=The Emancipation of Women in Interwar Belgrade and the \"Cvijeta Zuzori \u0107 \" Society|url=http://www.udi.rs/articles/genderRV.pdf|publisher=Yugoslav Association for Social History}}</ref>  [[David Albala]], her grandfather, was a physician and [[Zionist]] leader, who served for a period as president of [[Belgrade]]'s [[Sephardi]] community.<ref name=\"Radovi\u01072006\">{{Cite web |url=http://web.arhiv.rs/develop/vesti.nsf/feaee540dc011162c1256e7d0032cb98/c0b102b20bee7af8c1257128005d8e8a?OpenDocument |title=Evokacija Srpskog Feminizma S Po\u010detka 20. Veka  |last=Radovi\u0107 |first=Nade\u017eda |date=April 3, 2006 |publisher=Medijska Dokumentacija |language=Serbian |access-date=June 30, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://embassies.gov.il/beograd/NewsAndEvents/Pages/Marking-the-25th-anniversary-of-Israel-Serbia-diplomatic-relations-and-the-.aspx|title=25 Years of the Israel-Serbia Diplomatic Relations|date=December 25, 2017|website=Embassy of Israel|access-date=February 2, 2018}}</ref> At a young age, she displayed a keen interest in world culture, but was discouraged by her father from pursuit of a career in [[anthropology]]; instead she completed a [[Master of Business Administration]] degree.<ref name=huff/>\n\n==Wikipedia editing==\n[[File:Wikimedia Diversity Conference I.jpg|thumb|left|Stephenson-Goodknight at the 2016 Wikimedia Diversity Conference in Washington, D.C.]]\nStephenson-Goodknight began editing Wikipedia in 2007. Her son had edited an article about a town in Ukraine where he was working with the [[Peace Corps]], and told his mother that Wikipedia can be edited by anybody. She began editing later that year when she looked for books published by the [[Book League of America]] and found a gap in the site's knowledge resources.<ref name=\"WM profile\"/> She found the encyclopedia to be a suitable outlet for anthropology, citing [[Margaret Mead]] as an influence:<ref name=huff/><ref name=\"WMblog\">{{cite web|url=https://blog.wikimedia.org/2016/06/24/wikipedians-of-the-year/|title=Jimmy Wales names Emily Temple-Wood and Rosie Stephenson-Goodknight as Wikipedians of the Year|author=Erhart, Ed|publisher=Wikimedia Blog|date=June 24, 2016|accessdate=June 30, 2016 |language=}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|quote=Some of you know that I am a [[cultural anthropologist]] at heart. I wanted to follow in the footsteps of Margaret Mead and study cultural anthropology at Barnard (my mom\u2019s alma mater), like Margaret did. I wanted to travel to [[Papua New Guinea]] and do research on its people, like Margaret did. But my dad said \u2018no\u2019 to majoring in anthropology\u2014he wanted something more practical for my university studies. So now, years later, I get to live the life of an armchair cultural anthropologist, writing articles about Goaribari Island and its cannibals. To all the girls out there with impractical dreams, this article is dedicated to you.|author=|title=|source=}}\n\n[[File:Wikimania 2016 - Opening by Jimmy Wales 19.jpg|thumb|Stephenson-Goodknight at Wikimania 2016 with Wikipedia founder [[Jimmy Wales]]]]\n\nStephenson-Goodknight worked at creating articles on geography, architecture and various biographies for several years, but has more recently concentrated on women's biographies.<ref name=huff/> By 2013, Stephenson-Goodknight was featured in the UK ''[[The Huffington Post|Huffington Post]]'' for having written over 3,000 new articles for Wikipedia, and at that time, over 1000 articles had appeared at the \"Did you know?\" feature on Wikipedia's main page.<ref name=huff/> {{As of|2016}} she has created over 4,000 new articles,<ref group=Note>Total excludes redirects {{cite web|url=https://tools.wmflabs.org/xtools/pages/?user=Rosiestep&lang=en&wiki=wikipedia&namespace=0&redirects=none&limit=1000|title= Pages Created |website=WMFlabs |accessdate=July 8, 2016}}</ref> and has made over 100,000 edits.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"Counter\">{{cite web|title=X!'s tools|url=https://tools.wmflabs.org/xtools-ec/index.php?user=Rosiestep&project=en.wikipedia|website=wmflabs.org|accessdate=July 9, 2016}}</ref> The 2016 [[Wikipedian of the Year]] awards, granted by Wikipedia trustee [[Jimmy Wales]] in recognition of outstanding achievement, named Stephenson-Goodknight as a winner, sharing the award jointly with fellow editor [[Emily Temple-Wood]].<ref name=\":0\" /> At the time of the award, it was noted that over 1,300 of her articles have appeared on Wikipedia's \"Did you know?\".<ref name=\"WMblog\" /> She also co-founded WikiProject Women, WikiProject Women writers, and [[Women in Red]].<ref name=\"WMblog\"/> These projects have increased Wikipedia's percentage of articles on women from 15.5% to 16.35%.<ref name=union>{{cite news|url=http://www.theunion.com/news/localnews/22749884-113/nevada-citys-rosie-stephenson-goodknight-named-co-wikipedian-of-2016 | first=Teresa Yinmeng | last=Liu | title=Nevada City's Rosie Stephenson-Goodknight named co-Wikipedian of 2016 for addressing online gender gap|work=Western Nevada County Union|date=July 3, 2016|accessdate=July 6, 2016}}</ref> She has taken part in related projects such as the ''Art+Feminism Wikipedia Edit-A-Thon'' in April 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.library.unlv.edu/newsblog/2016/02/artfeminism-wikipedia-edit-thon.html|title=Art+Feminism Wikipedia Edit-A-Thon|publisher=University of Nevada, Las Vegas Libraries|date=February 2016|accessdate=June 30, 2016}}</ref>\n\nStephenson-Goodknight believes there is information to write stronger biographies, provided people are prepared to search for it.<ref name=grauniad>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2016/mar/19/women-in-science-on-wikipedia-will-we-ever-fill-the-information-gap|title=Women in science on Wikipedia: will we ever fill the information gap?|first=Molly|last=Redden|work=The Guardian|date=March 19, 2016|accessdate=June 30, 2016}}</ref> She also suggests it is possible for women to contribute greatly to Wikipedia, explaining, \"What Wikipedia needs is you, the female editor, with your unique aptitudes and interests and talkpage tone. Without you, gender imbalance and systemic bias continue on Wikipedia.\"<ref name=huff>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/netha-hussain/rosie-stephenson-the-woma_b_6302636.html|title=Rosie Stephenson: The Woman Who Wrote Over Three Thousand Articles on Wikipedia|last=Hussain | first=Netha|work=Huffington Post|date=February 9, 2015|accessdate=June 30, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nOn January 23, 2020, Stephenson-Goodknight was announced by Wikipedia to be the editor of the [[WP:6M|6,000,000<sup>th</sup> article]] on Wikipedia, namely the article on Canadian author [[Maria Elise Turner Lauder]]. <ref> [https://techcrunch.com/2020/01/23/wikipedia-english-six-million-articles/ Wikipedia now has more than 6 million articles in English], Manish Singh, January 23, 2020, techcrunch.com. </ref>\n\n==Awards and distinctions==\n[[File:Rosie Stephenson-Goodknight in Serbia 2.jpg|thumb|upright|Elevation to a Dame of the St. Sava Order of Diplomatic Pacifism, May 2018]]\nOn December 14, 2017, Goodnight was the \"honored guest\" at an event hosted by Israel's ambassador to Serbia, Alona Fisher-Kamm, to commemorate 25 years of diplomatic relations between Serbia and Israel.<ref name=\"D+C\">{{cite web|title=Interview with Rosie Gojich Stephenson-Goodknight: Everyone in Serbia made me feel like 'this is your home'|first=\u017dikica |last=Milo\u0161evi\u0107 |url=http://www.diplomacyandcommerce.rs/interview-with-rosie-gojich-stephenson-goodknight-everyone-in-serbia-made-me-feel-like-this-is-your-home/|website=Diplomacy&Commerce|date=March 2, 2018|accessdate=May 30, 2018|language=en-us}}</ref><ref name=\"EmbassyOfIsrael\">{{cite web|title=25 Years of the Israel-Serbia Diplomatic Relations|url=http://embassies.gov.il/beograd/NewsAndEvents/Pages/Marking-the-25th-anniversary-of-Israel-Serbia-diplomatic-relations-and-the-.aspx|publisher=Embassy of Israel in Serbia|accessdate=30 May 2018|date=25 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn May 29, 2018, in a ceremony conferring honors on those who deserved high diplomatic recognition, Stephenson-Goodnight was appointed a \"[[Knight of the St. Sava Order of Diplomatic Pacifism|Dame of the St. Sava Order of Diplomatic Pacifism]]\" ({{lang|sr|Vitez svetosavskog pacifizma}}) by Deputy Serbian Prime Minister and Minister of Foreign Affairs [[Ivica Da\u010di\u0107]],<ref name=\"Gproxx\">{{citation|author=|title=Serbian Diplomacy Day Marked|date=May 29, 2018|url=https://cordmagazine.com/events/faces-and-places/serbian-diplomacy-day-marked/|work=C or D|location=Belgrade|publisher=Alliance International Media}}<!-- identified as \"prof. Rosie Stephenson-Goodknight, Vice President of Wikimedia District of Columbia\" --></ref> for her work on Wikipedia to preserve the memory of Serbs in the \"hundred years since the Great War\". Mention was specifically made of her contribution towards preserving the memory of the Serbian military officer and Jewish community leader, her grandfather [[David Albala]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.blic.rs/vesti/politika/dacic-dodelio-najvisa-diplomatska-priznanja-medu-laureatima-modna-kreatorka/j3w5jjz|title=Da\u010di\u0107 dodelio najvi\u0161a diplomatska priznanja, me\u0111u laureatima modna kreatorka, humintarac, pre\u017eiveli logora\u0161i Jasenovca\u2026|newspaper=Blic|date=May 29, 2018|accessdate=May 29, 2018 |language=Serbian}}</ref><ref name=\"Gproxx\" />\n\n==Personal life==\nStephenson-Goodknight works in [[Las Vegas]] as a business administrator for a healthcare company, and has homes in that city and in [[Nevada City, California]].<ref name=union /><ref name=\"WM profile\">{{cite web|url=http://blog.wikimedia.org/2013/02/14/a-profile-of-rosie-stephenson-goodknight/|title=Finding inspiration from editing Wikipedia: a profile of Rosie Stephenson-Goodknight|first=Zoe|last=Bernard|publisher=Wikimedia Foundation|date=February 14, 2013|accessdate=June 30, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|United States}}\n* [[List of Wikipedia people]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=Note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Rosie Stephenson-Goodknight}}\n* [https://pro.europeana.eu/post/women-in-culture-and-tech-rosie-stephenson-goodknight Rosie Stephenson Goodknight on Europeana]\n\n{{Wikimedian of the Year|state=autocollapse}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stephenson-Goodknight, Rosie}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:American biographers]]\n[[Category:American encyclopedists]]\n[[Category:American people of Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Sephardic-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Serbian descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Serbian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American science writers]]\n[[Category:American Wikimedians]]\n[[Category:American women non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Knights of the St. Sava Order of Diplomatic Pacifism]]\n[[Category:People from Nevada City, California]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Serbian royalty]]\n[[Category:Wikimedians of the Year]]\n[[Category:Women biographers]]\n[[Category:Women science writers]]\n[[Category:Wikipedia people]]\n", "name_user": "Simeon", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eWikipedia editing:removed space, named ref", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rosie_Stephenson-Goodknight"}
